00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:00.560
[Amit Varma]: Ajay, welcome back to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:01.880
[Guest]: My pleasure to be here.

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:06.320
[Amit Varma]: So, Ajay, you're a big fan of the world of finance and the world of finance is,

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:12.240
[Amit Varma]: according to one kind of popular notion, a world full of villains where nothing productive is produced.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's like a giant casino where you have hot shot bankers playing with the real lives of people

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:21.160
[Amit Varma]: who have no control over what's going on.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Does finance deserve this kind of a bed wrap?

00:03:24.680 --> 00:03:30.960
[Guest]: My claim would be that finance is the best example of the seen and the unseen.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:39.920
[Guest]: That the grand drama playing out in financial markets and financial firms is the ultimate

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:45.840
[Guest]: foundation of all the prosperity and technology and innovation that we see around us today.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:47.320
[Guest]: That's a grand claim.

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:49.360
[Amit Varma]: So, start breaking it down for me.

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:52.760
[Guest]: OK, so we are used to the world of things.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:04:01.240
[Guest]: OK, we have a coffee, we have a cell phone, we buy things from firms and our immediate experiences

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:02.840
[Guest]: are always about those things.

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:09.280
[Guest]: We see the market economy as a world of things and we appreciate and admire and marvel at all the

00:04:09.280 --> 00:04:13.240
[Guest]: things that the wonderful market economy produces for us.

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:19.320
[Guest]: My shirt, my pants, all these joys, all these pleasures are given to us by the market economy.

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:20.880
[Guest]: That's the scene.

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:26.400
[Guest]: But now we should go one level deeper and ask, how does all this come about?

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:28.880
[Guest]: Where do the firms come from?

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:31.120
[Guest]: Where do the innovations come from?

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:33.920
[Guest]: Where do the decisions of the firms come from?

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:35.920
[Guest]: And this is where we get to finance.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:38.920
[Guest]: OK, so it is finance that puts the firms there.

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:42.240
[Guest]: It is finance that tells the firms what to do.

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:46.840
[Guest]: It is finance that creates the incentives for the innovation.

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:57.080
[Guest]: So, my first level idea would be that the scene world is being invisibly controlled and shaped and

00:04:57.080 --> 00:05:01.400
[Guest]: influenced every day by the world of finance.

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:04.760
[Guest]: OK, and so let me start with the simplest of all examples.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:13.960
[Guest]: I want to go back to the 1990s, when somewhere in the late 1990s, people started getting the idea that,

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:16.720
[Guest]: you know, you could build a software services company in India.

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:18.960
[Guest]: This was not a mainstream idea for a long time.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:25.440
[Guest]: Most people don't remember that in 1994, when Infosys did the IPO, it actually did not succeed so well.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:29.840
[Guest]: It was not a hot IPO in 1994, as you might imagine today.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:39.200
[Guest]: It's only by the late 90s that the idea got around that you can actually run a big, successful

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:41.960
[Guest]: software services company in India and make a lot of money.

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest]: And where did that idea go off?

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.520
[Guest]: It went off in the heads of the finance guys.

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:47.760
[Guest]: What did they do?

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:55.800
[Guest]: They drove up the prices of the shares of the software services companies, the early pioneers like Infosys.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:02.360
[Guest]: So what that did was it created this publicly visible price, the share price, the valuation, the P.E.

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:09.080
[Guest]: ratio, the price to book ratio of these software services companies was stratospheric.

00:06:09.840 --> 00:06:14.280
[Guest]: And all around the country, there were people who started looking at those prices and wondering,

00:06:14.280 --> 00:06:16.240
[Guest]: you know what, should I be doing something there?

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:24.680
[Guest]: OK, so I was there and I vividly recollect that the, you know, the people who started looking at those

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:31.920
[Guest]: prices, the financial system was shouting out to everybody in the country that if you put 100 rupees

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:36.760
[Guest]: and build a successful cement company, we will reward you with wealth of 70 rupees.

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:42.840
[Guest]: OK, in other words, don't bother building a cement company, but if you put 100 rupees and succeed in

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:46.120
[Guest]: building a software company, then we'll give you a wealth of 500 rupees.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:48.160
[Guest]: That's a price to book ratio of five.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:54.440
[Guest]: And sure enough, there were attentive people all around the country who are watching that drama

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:56.280
[Guest]: playing out in the stock prices.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:01.240
[Guest]: And so you had literally thousands of people in India who started wondering, could we start a

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:05.080
[Guest]: software company? Do I have a friend who knows how to build software?

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:11.760
[Guest]: Do I have a cousin that knows how to sell software in London or in Sydney and so on?

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:16.800
[Guest]: So all across the country, the thought process started springing up that we should really be

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:20.560
[Guest]: building a software company. And also, we should really not be building a cement company.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:28.480
[Guest]: All these decisions all across the country were invisibly coordinated by one thing, the stock

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:33.440
[Guest]: market, the valuation of the stock market, reshaped the thought process, the development of

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:35.520
[Guest]: business plans all around the country.

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:42.080
[Amit Varma]: So would it be fair to say that just as in the marketplace of things per se, let's say that I am

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:48.160
[Amit Varma]: someone who can make a widget for 40 rupees, and I see that day in the market, it's selling for 80

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:50.240
[Amit Varma]: rupees, and that's an incentive for me to go in.

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:52.480
[Amit Varma]: So the prices are giving me that information.

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:56.320
[Amit Varma]: So similarly, what you're seeing is that what the stock market tells you what the world of

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.840
[Amit Varma]: finance tells you is that software stocks are shooting up, and you're increasing the

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:02.800
[Amit Varma]: incentives for more and more people to get into it.

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Is there a danger of reflexivity here in the sense that can you create a vicious cycle where a

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:13.200
[Amit Varma]: bubble forms, which is then inevitably going to come down as a dot-com bubble did?

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:17.280
[Guest]: So now I want to go to the thought process inside the stock market.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:19.040
[Guest]: And that will give us more insight.

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:21.920
[Guest]: The stock market is not some magical construct.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:23.360
[Guest]: It's just composed of people.

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:25.600
[Guest]: It's composed of people like you and me.

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:32.320
[Guest]: And the prices at which trades take place reflect the views of people.

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:33.680
[Guest]: So those are smart people.

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:35.600
[Guest]: They are looking at all the available information.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:37.520
[Amit Varma]: So that's your demand side basically reflecting it.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:41.280
[Guest]: Wait, I just want to highlight the limitations of the process.

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:45.680
[Guest]: The people who are trading the shares are looking at the world, are commanding information

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:49.840
[Guest]: about the world, are trying to make forecasts about the world, and these forecasts will

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:50.960
[Guest]: necessarily go wrong.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:52.320
[Guest]: And that's perfectly OK.

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:54.160
[Guest]: The future will always be unknowable.

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:55.280
[Guest]: Some things will go wrong.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:57.440
[Guest]: So every now and then there will be mistakes.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:02.160
[Guest]: We should not think about this as some flawless central planning system where decisions will

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:03.200
[Guest]: always be perfect.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:06.640
[Guest]: So yes, what you call a bubble, I call mistakes.

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:11.440
[Guest]: Mistakes will always happen, that there will be a time when everybody thinks that nanotechnology

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:16.080
[Guest]: is going to work and there will be a rush of investment into nanotechnology firms.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:18.960
[Guest]: And some years later, people will think, nah, that didn't really work.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:22.720
[Guest]: We did not really make money in that and there will be money that is wasted.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:23.280
[Guest]: And that's OK.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:24.320
[Guest]: That's a part of life.

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:30.240
[Guest]: The point is that the stock market is the place where a lot of smart people come together

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:36.720
[Guest]: and form views about the future and not just write blog articles about those views, but

00:09:36.720 --> 00:09:38.240
[Guest]: put their money where their mouth is.

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:43.520
[Guest]: People do trades with real money and do their best in trying to forecast the future.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:49.520
[Guest]: So there is a remarkable alignment between the personal self-interest of the people trading

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:56.880
[Guest]: the market and the connections between the prices that are produced and the allocation

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:58.320
[Guest]: of resources in society.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:03.600
[Guest]: So there is self-interest part and then there is a positive externalities part.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:05.680
[Guest]: These prices create positive externalities.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:11.920
[Guest]: The whole country benefits because we are able to run a self-organizing system surrounding

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:12.640
[Guest]: those prices.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:15.760
[Guest]: So everybody knows the price to book of a hospital.

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:19.840
[Guest]: Now, thousands of people all over the country will wonder, should I start a hospital?

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:21.360
[Guest]: Should I not start a hospital?

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:24.160
[Guest]: But doesn't this create a set of two incentives?

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:28.960
[Amit Varma]: For example, earlier, if you're starting a business, your incentive is can I make a profit?

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:32.480
[Amit Varma]: Can I create a product for 40 rupees which somebody will buy for 60 rupees?

00:10:32.480 --> 00:10:33.520
[Amit Varma]: So that's my profit.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:38.080
[Amit Varma]: But now there's another incentive which comes in where this profit in the marketplace of

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:39.200
[Amit Varma]: things doesn't matter.

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:44.640
[Amit Varma]: That, you know, can I have an IPO and am I in the sector which is hot right now, which

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:49.120
[Amit Varma]: could be dot com once upon a time, which could be, say, biotech right now, and it doesn't

00:10:49.120 --> 00:10:52.560
[Amit Varma]: matter what the product is and whether it ever makes a profit as long as the stock

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:53.600
[Guest]: market value is high.

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:55.760
[Guest]: Well, in the end, people do want profit.

00:10:55.760 --> 00:11:00.960
[Guest]: So I think the financial system has demonstrated the ability to invest for long time periods

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:02.400
[Guest]: in losing propositions.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:07.200
[Guest]: So in fact, 10 years ago, the criticism or 20 years ago, the criticism would have been

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:10.800
[Guest]: that the short term attention to profit is a mistake.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:16.720
[Guest]: Well, today we've seen many sectors, most notably clean energy, where the financial

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:21.760
[Guest]: system understood maybe 10 years ago that global warming was a problem and there is

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:28.320
[Guest]: going to need to be gigantic development of technologies and infrastructure around clean

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:29.120
[Guest]: energy.

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:34.400
[Guest]: And the financial system was willing to commit very large resources into these firms, even

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.240
[Guest]: though they were presently not making money.

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:41.920
[Guest]: But it was the bet of people in the financial system that, you know, give it time, it's

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:43.120
[Guest]: going to make money in the future.

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:47.360
[Guest]: So the stock price is just the net present value of all the dividends that are going

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:48.480
[Guest]: to come out in the future.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:50.080
[Guest]: Nobody is here for charity.

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:54.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a great example that you gave me when we were chatting about this before of

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:59.440
[Amit Varma]: how a bet by the stock markets actually makes a huge impact in the real world is what happened

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:02.880
[Amit Varma]: in the late 1990s when, you know, optical cabling, for example.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:09.120
[Guest]: Yeah, so optical communications is a late 90s, early 2000s revolution, which was led

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:10.240
[Guest]: by the financial system.

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:15.040
[Guest]: People understood that there is going to be an explosion of data and we need a whole new

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:21.840
[Guest]: generation of switches and computing capabilities surrounding mind-blowing levels of bandwidth.

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest]: And there was a series of startups which got large investment by the venture capitalists.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:29.520
[Guest]: And it actually worked out well.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:35.040
[Guest]: And we got that gigantic escalation of capabilities inside many of those engineering

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:35.520
[Guest]: companies.

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:40.720
[Guest]: So the role of the financial system is to look into the future and translate that into

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:43.280
[Guest]: a structure of payoffs for entrepreneurs.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:47.760
[Guest]: So in our old world of Hayek and the world of things, we would be talking the profit

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:48.720
[Guest]: rate of a company.

00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:50.720
[Guest]: We'd be talking about the profit for one year.

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:55.920
[Guest]: What finance does is it takes profits over many years and turns that into a net present

00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:56.400
[Guest]: value.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:01.120
[Guest]: And also it brings the word risk into the equation, which is, of course, important.

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.080
[Guest]: So risk and reward come together in finance.

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:10.800
[Guest]: And what finance does ultimately is it creates a structure of incentives for what industries

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:16.320
[Guest]: should expand, what kinds of tools and technologies and products are going to be important in

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:17.200
[Guest]: the future.

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:22.080
[Guest]: And it sends out incentives for firms and managers and entrepreneurs to build those

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:23.280
[Guest]: kinds of capabilities.

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:28.160
[Guest]: And that's the invisible way in which the phrase is used that Wall Street runs Main

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:32.960
[Guest]: Street, that Wall Street figures out these prices and then Main Street responds to those

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:33.760
[Amit Varma]: prices.

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that those incentives also work in drawing the best minds to finance

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:39.840
[Amit Varma]: because there is so much money to be made.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.760
[Amit Varma]: The best minds come to finance.

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And when they are putting their money where their mouth is, you have to take that seriously.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.040
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, you have the best minds coming together for good incentives, setting the

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:51.760
[Amit Varma]: agenda for...

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:53.920
[Guest]: So I have mixed feelings on this.

00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:56.640
[Guest]: So first, I don't think that there's a shortage of minds.

00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:57.200
[Guest]: Okay.

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:01.120
[Guest]: So I think there's a very large supply of wonderful people in the world.

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:03.920
[Guest]: And I don't think that there is a shortage of minds.

00:14:03.920 --> 00:14:05.840
[Guest]: Some good minds come into podcasting as well.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:06.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:11.040
[Guest]: So I think that there is a great deal of brilliant and wonderful humans all over the world in

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:13.920
[Guest]: many, many lives and careers and professions.

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:20.480
[Guest]: So some people have a negative view that there's a PhD physics guy who's now trading in a hedge

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:22.560
[Guest]: fund, and that's a bad use for society.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.360
[Guest]: And I don't agree.

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.520
[Guest]: I think there's no shortage of talent.

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:26.560
[Guest]: That's one point.

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:28.160
[Guest]: My second point is that, yes, exactly.

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:33.280
[Guest]: As you say, you need to bring in some of the best capabilities into finance because finance

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:34.320
[Guest]: is that important.

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:40.160
[Guest]: I mean, finance has to think about the world, form views about the future and reshape the

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:41.040
[Guest]: world around us.

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: So we see this most vividly in the high technology space where many a successful engineer and

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.320
[Guest]: entrepreneur starts a second life as a venture capitalist.

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:52.480
[Guest]: Okay.

00:14:52.480 --> 00:14:59.360
[Guest]: So for example, the great engineer Bill Joy, who was one of the key people in BSD Unix,

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:04.560
[Guest]: one of the founders of Sun Microsystems, then turned into a partner at Kleiner Perkins.

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:09.760
[Guest]: And that's the kind of genius that is applying its mind to thinking about what investments,

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:10.400
[Amit Varma]: what industry.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:12.320
[Amit Varma]: Like his co-founder at Sunway North Coast Line.

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:13.680
[Guest]: Who is also a venture capitalist.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And you've described finance as the brain of the economy and use venture capitalism.

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:23.440
[Guest]: Joseph Stiglitz says that finance is the brain of the economy.

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.280
[Amit Varma]: So break that down for me.

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:30.320
[Guest]: So all this thinking work is what Joseph Stiglitz calls the brain of the economy.

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:32.240
[Guest]: That it is finance that has to think.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:34.560
[Guest]: It is finance that awards valuations.

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:39.040
[Guest]: It is finance that is like the commanding heights of the economy, to use a Nehruvian

00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:43.440
[Guest]: term, what you would have thought the planning commission would do.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:47.840
[Guest]: That the planning commission will decide that, you know what, we need to build integrated

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:48.320
[Guest]: circuits.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:49.920
[Guest]: We need a VLSI fab in India.

00:15:49.920 --> 00:15:52.640
[Guest]: We don't need a VLSI fab in India.

00:15:52.640 --> 00:15:56.800
[Guest]: These are all the things that are ultimately now controlled by the financial system.

00:15:56.800 --> 00:16:01.280
[Guest]: So that is why Joseph Stiglitz calls finance the brain of the economy.

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:04.800
[Guest]: My good friend Josh Feldman tells a very interesting story.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:07.440
[Guest]: He says that suppose there was an earthquake.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:09.920
[Guest]: I think you were there when he told this story.

00:16:09.920 --> 00:16:13.280
[Guest]: He said, suppose there is an earthquake and the entire Bombay gets destroyed.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:13.600
[Guest]: Okay.

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:16.640
[Guest]: And suppose we had to pick up the pieces and start over.

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:18.320
[Guest]: What is the first thing that we would do?

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:18.960
[Guest]: Answer.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:21.120
[Guest]: We would rebuild the financial system.

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:25.280
[Guest]: Because the financial system would then fund everybody else and the rest of Bombay would

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:25.680
[Amit Varma]: get built.

00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:27.680
[Amit Varma]: So before you build the schools, build the banks.

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:28.560
[Guest]: Everything will flow from there.

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:32.240
[Guest]: The first thing you got to get in place is the financial system.

00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:35.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's sort of a very telling analogy of a planning commission as say something

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:39.520
[Amit Varma]: that's doing central planning, but it's centralized and it cannot possibly have access

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:43.360
[Amit Varma]: to all the information and therefore it invariably messes up.

00:16:43.360 --> 00:16:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But this is sort of the brain of the economy, but all the information is decentralized.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:48.720
[Guest]: It's coming from.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:50.320
[Guest]: It's a self-organizing brain.

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:50.720
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:55.760
[Guest]: So we combine the brain, but yet it's a self-organizing system and there's no compulsion.

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:56.720
[Guest]: There's no coercion.

00:16:56.720 --> 00:16:57.200
[Guest]: Okay.

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:57.840
[Guest]: You're welcome.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:16:58.720
[Guest]: I'm welcome.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:02.560
[Guest]: Everybody's free to look at the system of prices and disagree that.

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:03.520
[Guest]: No, I don't agree.

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:06.240
[Guest]: I think aluminum is much more important than you guys think it is.

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:06.800
[Guest]: Very good.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:08.320
[Guest]: Put your money where your mouth is.

00:17:08.320 --> 00:17:11.600
[Guest]: Buy aluminum futures or buy the shares of aluminum companies.

00:17:11.600 --> 00:17:13.760
[Amit Varma]: And where does a VC get his signals from?

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Where does he get his, what are his incentives?

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:17.520
[Guest]: Where does he get his knowledge from?

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:18.480
[Guest]: By looking at the world.

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:22.880
[Guest]: So the VC's job is supposed to be to look at the world and figure, I think these technologies

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:23.840
[Guest]: are going to be important.

00:17:23.840 --> 00:17:25.520
[Guest]: These business models are going to be important.

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And the markets are a reflection of that, the stock markets.

00:17:27.840 --> 00:17:32.240
[Guest]: So the VC turns around and shapes the projects.

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:33.680
[Guest]: The VC is looking in the future.

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:37.680
[Guest]: And also remember the VC likes to take his project ultimately IPO.

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:41.440
[Guest]: So the VC needs to look at the stock market.

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:46.720
[Guest]: So the stock market says what kind of price to book ratios are attractive and the VC is

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:48.720
[Guest]: guided by the possibility.

00:17:48.720 --> 00:17:53.600
[Guest]: For example, Indian healthcare, Indian NBFCs, when these price to book ratios were very

00:17:53.600 --> 00:17:58.080
[Guest]: high, we got a surge of private equity funds building projects in these areas.

00:17:58.960 --> 00:17:59.200
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:05.280
[Amit Varma]: And what about more arcane forms of finance like derivatives or like the kind of complex

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:08.000
[Amit Varma]: instruments that led to the 2008 crash?

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.160
[Guest]: So far, I've talked about the stock market.

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:11.920
[Guest]: I've emphasized the share price.

00:18:11.920 --> 00:18:12.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.280
[Amit Varma]: Now, there are two more things that need to go into this.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:18.560
[Guest]: That need to go into this and both of them connect to derivatives.

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:23.120
[Guest]: The first is that, OK, suppose you're this super smart guy and you have an opinion that

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.240
[Guest]: the share price of Infosys is going to do well.

00:18:26.240 --> 00:18:27.200
[Guest]: You have two choices.

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:31.600
[Guest]: Case one, you will put down 100 rupees and buy the shares of Infosys.

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:38.400
[Guest]: Case two, you will put down 25 rupees and get a position on 100 rupees of Infosys.

00:18:38.400 --> 00:18:40.240
[Guest]: OK, so you get a four times leverage.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:44.480
[Guest]: By only putting 25, you get position of 100.

00:18:44.480 --> 00:18:46.400
[Guest]: You're going to prefer the leveraged position.

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:52.880
[Guest]: OK, so for people with too much brains and not much money, you are benefited by having

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:54.000
[Guest]: a leveraged position.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:55.680
[Guest]: And that is what the derivatives do.

00:18:55.680 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: So financial derivatives allow the injection of knowledge and ideas into the process of

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.760
[Guest]: price discovery while giving a magnification where people who have more brains and not

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:12.240
[Guest]: enough money are able to participate in the price formation process.

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:19.600
[Guest]: The other side of the derivatives is derivatives trading on physical commodities, whether it

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:23.840
[Guest]: is aluminum or wheat or butter or eggs.

00:19:23.840 --> 00:19:27.920
[Guest]: These are very important markets that directly link to the physicals.

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:32.720
[Guest]: So there you directly see that six months from now, eggs are going to be expensive.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:37.280
[Guest]: So you start getting incentives to build more eggs starting from today.

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:41.680
[Guest]: So the derivatives markets there directly connect into the world of things.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:46.480
[Amit Varma]: And this is not some abstract thing, you know, people sitting in Wall Street offices do.

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:47.920
[Amit Varma]: This has a very real impact.

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:52.480
[Amit Varma]: And one field in which you've pointed out where it could help, and I had an episode

00:19:52.480 --> 00:19:56.720
[Amit Varma]: on this a long, long time ago with Karthik Shashtar on futures markets in agriculture,

00:19:56.720 --> 00:20:00.320
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, people just hear the phrase futures market in agriculture and they're

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:01.200
[Amit Varma]: like, what the hell?

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:03.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, we have, you know, the agriculture is in a crisis.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:06.560
[Amit Varma]: You need to kind of, you know, there are enough problems in the real world.

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:08.080
[Amit Varma]: Why would you gamble with it?

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:12.480
[Amit Varma]: But your point is that a lot of the problems of agriculture and the problems of the common

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:16.320
[Amit Varma]: humble farmer can be sorted out if there are futures markets in agriculture.

00:20:16.320 --> 00:20:17.760
[Guest]: And I would tell that in two steps.

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:19.600
[Guest]: So let's start from the world of things.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:24.320
[Guest]: I think it is useful to see that there are two very big decisions that are made in the

00:20:24.320 --> 00:20:25.280
[Guest]: world of food.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:27.120
[Guest]: Question one, what do I sow?

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:29.520
[Guest]: Question two, what do I store?

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:32.720
[Guest]: Okay, these are the two decisions that are made.

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: The rest is lotteries.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.600
[Guest]: Okay, so I sow something, but the rain doesn't come or the locusts come.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:39.600
[Guest]: So there are many other shocks that come along.

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:44.800
[Guest]: But in terms of the decisions made by real people in the world of food, there are two

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:45.840
[Guest]: decisions above all.

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:47.360
[Guest]: Question one, what to sow?

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:49.040
[Guest]: Question two, what to store?

00:20:49.040 --> 00:20:50.720
[Guest]: Okay, how do you make those decisions?

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:53.760
[Guest]: For these decisions, you need to have a view about the future.

00:20:53.760 --> 00:20:55.600
[Guest]: You need to have a forecast about the future.

00:20:55.600 --> 00:21:01.280
[Guest]: What we see in India every now and then is something that comes out of a model that was

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:05.360
[Guest]: written by the economist Paul Samuelson many, many decades ago.

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:07.120
[Guest]: Okay, he calls it the cobweb model.

00:21:07.120 --> 00:21:10.880
[Guest]: Okay, that's a story that runs like this, that there's a shortage of tomatoes.

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:12.640
[Guest]: The tomatoes are very expensive.

00:21:12.640 --> 00:21:15.120
[Guest]: So lots of farmers rush in and sow tomatoes.

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:16.640
[Guest]: So then you get a great surge.

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: You get a huge crop of tomatoes.

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: The price of tomatoes crashes.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:22.480
[Guest]: And then farmers get very unhappy.

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: And then they do not sow tomatoes.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.680
[Guest]: And then the cycle starts all over again.

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:27.120
[Guest]: Okay, this is called the cobweb model.

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:31.520
[Guest]: And this is just a cycle of sadness that you're screwed when there's a glut of tomatoes.

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:33.600
[Guest]: You're screwed when there's a shortage of tomatoes.

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:35.040
[Guest]: And this thing just goes on.

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:36.400
[Guest]: How do you break this cycle?

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:39.040
[Guest]: The answer lies in futures trading.

00:21:39.040 --> 00:21:43.760
[Guest]: What you need is a futures market to say that, look, six months from now, we believe the

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:45.600
[Guest]: price of eggs will be so much.

00:21:45.600 --> 00:21:51.760
[Guest]: Six months from now, we are able to see the prospective outcome of the Kharif harvest

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:52.960
[Guest]: of India today.

00:21:52.960 --> 00:22:00.240
[Guest]: Now, if that information was produced by a deep and liquid and active market, then a

00:22:00.240 --> 00:22:04.240
[Guest]: sowing decision could be taken by using that public good of the price.

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:08.480
[Guest]: Okay, so as a farmer, I could choose to use that information.

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:09.920
[Guest]: What will be the price of wheat?

00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:11.280
[Guest]: What will be the price of rice?

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:12.720
[Guest]: What are all my alternatives?

00:22:12.720 --> 00:22:14.560
[Guest]: What are all the future prices?

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:20.640
[Guest]: Come October, when the Kharif harvest comes out, I see all the futures prices.

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:24.160
[Guest]: And based on that, I work out my profits and I choose to sow one.

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:26.720
[Guest]: Okay, that's an incredible information resource.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:30.320
[Amit Varma]: So your farmer is then guided by the wisdom of crowds.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:33.040
[Amit Varma]: Whereas otherwise, look, the farmer is gambling anyway.

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.640
[Amit Varma]: But here he has far more information if there are good futures markets for him to gamble.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:38.320
[Guest]: And it's much more than information.

00:22:38.320 --> 00:22:40.160
[Guest]: The futures market is not just an opinion.

00:22:40.160 --> 00:22:41.360
[Guest]: It's not an opinion poll.

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:43.280
[Guest]: People are putting their money where their mouth is.

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: So the farmer can choose to actually enter into a contract to sell goods at Dusshera

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:54.080
[Guest]: when the Kharif harvest comes out at that price that is visible in the futures market.

00:22:54.080 --> 00:22:55.520
[Guest]: So it's not just an opinion poll.

00:22:55.520 --> 00:22:57.360
[Guest]: It's not a hypothetical view of the future.

00:22:57.360 --> 00:22:59.360
[Guest]: It is people putting their money where their mouth is.

00:22:59.360 --> 00:23:01.920
[Guest]: And then he's guaranteed that, okay, I will get that price.

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:03.920
[Guest]: And he has other risks.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:05.600
[Guest]: There is a crop failure problem.

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:08.080
[Guest]: There is a locust problem, many other problems.

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:12.240
[Guest]: But at least price risk is something that futures markets excel at doing.

00:23:12.240 --> 00:23:12.560
[Guest]: Okay.

00:23:12.560 --> 00:23:14.720
[Guest]: And again, the seen and the unseen.

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:17.440
[Guest]: Many people want that proof of truth.

00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:22.560
[Guest]: They want to see if the farmer is directly selling goods on the futures market.

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:24.320
[Guest]: You think the futures market is useful.

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:26.320
[Guest]: And I think that's a very incomplete view of the world.

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:30.400
[Guest]: The futures market is useful if it reshapes the structure of information.

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:32.480
[Guest]: If it changes the way people think.

00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:32.960
[Guest]: Full stop.

00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:34.800
[Guest]: You don't have to have direct participation.

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:35.120
[Guest]: Okay.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:37.840
[Guest]: And now let me come to part two, which is the storage decision.

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:38.720
[Guest]: Okay.

00:23:38.720 --> 00:23:41.920
[Guest]: So I'm a person who has capital, who has a warehouse.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:45.920
[Guest]: And I see a price of wheat on the spot market today.

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:50.080
[Guest]: And I see the price of wheat six months into the future on the futures market.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:50.480
[Guest]: Okay.

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:53.600
[Guest]: And if I see a good gap between the two, then I think to myself,

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:56.640
[Guest]: why don't I buy goods on the spot market and put them in a warehouse?

00:23:57.280 --> 00:23:57.600
[Guest]: Okay.

00:23:57.600 --> 00:23:59.200
[Guest]: That's a storage decision.

00:23:59.200 --> 00:24:01.760
[Guest]: So thousands of storage decisions all around the country

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:05.760
[Guest]: are taken by using the futures price as a reference.

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:10.400
[Guest]: And maybe entering into a contract also to sell through the futures exchange.

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:11.360
[Guest]: But it doesn't need to be.

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:14.320
[Guest]: The futures price is a public good.

00:24:14.320 --> 00:24:16.800
[Guest]: And it can reshape the decisions of storage.

00:24:16.800 --> 00:24:21.440
[Guest]: And you can see how the sewing decision and the storage decision are both very important.

00:24:21.440 --> 00:24:26.880
[Guest]: So if people will not store at the right time, it will generate a glut on the spot market.

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:33.360
[Guest]: So you want this entire machinery that in June, when the Kharif sewing is being done,

00:24:33.360 --> 00:24:35.040
[Guest]: you want a good sewing decision.

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:39.280
[Guest]: In October, when the crop comes out, you want a good storage decision.

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:43.440
[Guest]: All these decisions are coordinated by the futures market.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.480
[Amit Varma]: How do agriculture future markets work in other countries?

00:24:46.480 --> 00:24:48.480
[Guest]: This is exactly how they work in other countries.

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:48.720
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:54.560
[Amit Varma]: And what is sort of, is it again a mindset problem for why Indian policymakers don't

00:24:54.560 --> 00:24:58.960
[Amit Varma]: let these happen or other interest groups which benefit from these not happening?

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:04.880
[Guest]: So I think we have a lot of baggage, emotional baggage around hoarding of food.

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:10.720
[Guest]: We have a skepticism about trading.

00:25:10.720 --> 00:25:12.320
[Guest]: I think we think trading is a bad thing.

00:25:13.120 --> 00:25:17.600
[Guest]: So some of these primeval fears keep coming up from time to time.

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:21.120
[Guest]: And we've done a great deal of government interventions

00:25:21.120 --> 00:25:24.960
[Guest]: that have limited the ability of the futures market to work.

