00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:38.800
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene in the Unseen.

00:27:38.800 --> 00:27:43.600
[Amit Varma]: I am chatting with Voldemort Ajay Shah about the evil world of finance,

00:27:43.600 --> 00:27:45.200
[Amit Varma]: which sucks hope from us.

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:48.480
[Amit Varma]: So you're making the case that that's quite the opposite.

00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:54.160
[Guest]: I think that finance is the invisible knowledge and information system

00:27:54.160 --> 00:27:56.000
[Guest]: that runs the market economy.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Now, one interesting point that you made,

00:27:57.760 --> 00:27:59.280
[Amit Varma]: which I'd like you to elaborate on,

00:27:59.280 --> 00:28:03.760
[Amit Varma]: is that financial markets also set the price of time.

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Explain this.

00:28:05.440 --> 00:28:08.720
[Guest]: I want to borrow money today that I will repay you next year.

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:10.160
[Guest]: Okay, so that's an interest rate.

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:13.280
[Guest]: That's the price of that delay of one year.

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:14.160
[Guest]: And it could be two years.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:14.880
[Guest]: It could be five years.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:15.680
[Guest]: It could be 30 years.

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:20.000
[Guest]: This price is discovered on the bond market.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:24.480
[Guest]: So there is a giant edifice called the bond market where there are traders.

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:30.560
[Guest]: Some people in the economy want to put money in today and get it out tomorrow.

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:34.240
[Guest]: Some people want to take money today and return it tomorrow.

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:38.320
[Guest]: And all these relationships are sold out on the bond market.

00:28:38.320 --> 00:28:42.080
[Guest]: And bottom line, the bond market delivers a number to the economy.

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:46.320
[Guest]: It's an information system that delivers the price of time to the economy.

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:50.800
[Guest]: So whether you're going to take a home loan or you're going to build a bridge,

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:54.800
[Guest]: this is the infrastructure that makes it possible.

00:28:54.800 --> 00:29:00.800
[Guest]: So the noisy, tumultuous process of trading and speculation

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:06.080
[Guest]: and bond market, bond futures, all that stuff results in one outcome.

00:29:06.080 --> 00:29:09.200
[Guest]: And that outcome is the economy understands the price of time.

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:11.520
[Guest]: And that is, again, not an opinion poll.

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:14.560
[Guest]: It is people who are putting their money where their mouth is.

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:18.960
[Guest]: So when you build a bridge and you are going to borrow for 10 years

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:23.280
[Guest]: or 20 years in order to be able to pay for that bridge up front,

00:29:24.080 --> 00:29:27.360
[Guest]: you are the user of this market in time.

00:29:28.080 --> 00:29:30.560
[Guest]: So all long dated projects, which involve borrowing,

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:36.720
[Guest]: ultimately feed off the giant public markets in the form of the bond market.

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:39.200
[Amit Varma]: How does the central bank fit into all this?

00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:40.880
[Amit Varma]: And if they're setting interest rates and so on?

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:43.440
[Guest]: The central bank controls the short term interest rate.

00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:45.200
[Guest]: In a proper market economy,

00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:48.240
[Guest]: the central bank should only control the short term interest rate.

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:50.240
[Guest]: So it could be at a one day horizon.

00:29:50.240 --> 00:29:51.920
[Guest]: It could be at a one week horizon.

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:55.920
[Guest]: All other rates should be discovered by the market economy.

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:59.040
[Guest]: OK, now this may often not be the world that we live in.

00:29:59.040 --> 00:30:02.240
[Guest]: We may often have interventions by the government

00:30:02.240 --> 00:30:05.600
[Guest]: in trying to reshape interest rates at different maturities.

00:30:05.600 --> 00:30:11.360
[Guest]: But that's part of the larger agenda of the role of the price system in India.

00:30:11.360 --> 00:30:14.800
[Guest]: But in a conceptual frame and what we see happening

00:30:14.800 --> 00:30:17.280
[Guest]: in mature market economies all over the world

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:20.800
[Guest]: is that the role of monetary policy is to control the short term interest rate.

00:30:20.800 --> 00:30:24.560
[Guest]: After that, all other rates are produced by the private sector.

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:27.600
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps this is a subject for a separate episode on its own.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:31.280
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is that if we know that just allowing markets to function

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:34.480
[Amit Varma]: and set the price of everything is overwhelmingly good for society

00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:36.240
[Amit Varma]: and any interference with that is a problem,

00:30:36.880 --> 00:30:40.480
[Amit Varma]: then why an exception in the case of the central bank setting short term interest rates?

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:43.600
[Guest]: That is subject for a separate episode.

00:30:44.240 --> 00:30:48.240
[Guest]: It turns out that the creation of fiat money intrinsically comes with that one lever.

00:30:48.880 --> 00:30:53.200
[Guest]: So in the olden days, we used to say the central bank controls the printing presses.

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:56.800
[Guest]: OK, the moment you decide to build fiat money,

00:30:56.800 --> 00:30:58.080
[Guest]: you control that printing press.

00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:02.000
[Guest]: We are now in what is called a Wicksellian world

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.560
[Guest]: where the printing press is controlled by this decision to set the short rate.

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:10.000
[Guest]: And it turns out that by controlling the short rate,

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:13.520
[Guest]: we're able to exercise a stabilizing force on the business cycle.

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:15.920
[Amit Varma]: So that's why that one rate is special.

00:31:15.920 --> 00:31:21.280
[Amit Varma]: Now tell me about, you so far told me how the financial system is a brain of the economy.

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:24.400
[Amit Varma]: Wall Street today determines what Main Street will do tomorrow,

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:27.120
[Amit Varma]: how the information plays out, how the incentives play out.

00:31:27.680 --> 00:31:28.480
[Amit Varma]: All of that is great.

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:33.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, whenever I hear, whenever I think of well-functioning markets, I also worry about

00:31:33.520 --> 00:31:35.920
[Amit Varma]: a well-meaning state messing it all up.

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:40.480
[Amit Varma]: What are the different ways in which the state can interfere with financial markets?

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:44.160
[Guest]: So I have described a world where the financial markets work well.

00:31:44.800 --> 00:31:48.160
[Guest]: OK, by default, financial markets do not necessarily work well.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:49.680
[Guest]: And there are market failures.

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:58.080
[Guest]: So the classes of market failure that we see in finance is there is an externalities problem.

00:31:58.080 --> 00:32:04.560
[Guest]: If there is collapse of a financial firm or a collapse of the financial market system,

00:32:04.560 --> 00:32:07.200
[Guest]: it imposes harm upon innocent bystanders.

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:08.960
[Guest]: So there is an externalities problem.

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:15.280
[Guest]: There is an asymmetric information problem in that when you are the user of a bank,

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:18.560
[Guest]: you do not know the soundness of the bank.

00:32:18.560 --> 00:32:21.760
[Guest]: You do not know whether the bank will actually live up to its promises.

00:32:22.400 --> 00:32:24.960
[Guest]: So it's an unreasonable amount of effort.

00:32:24.960 --> 00:32:30.160
[Guest]: It's a bit like a food safety thing that if you and I go buy medicines in a shop,

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:33.360
[Guest]: we can't be expected to test the purity of the medicine.

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:38.640
[Guest]: So like that, there is an asymmetric information problem in the statements that the

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:42.720
[Guest]: financial firms make to their consumers.

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:47.440
[Guest]: So these two problems require a set of regulatory interventions.

00:32:47.440 --> 00:32:52.720
[Guest]: OK, and the regulatory interventions in finance basically fall into four categories.

00:32:52.720 --> 00:32:55.280
[Guest]: Case one is called consumer protection,

00:32:55.280 --> 00:33:00.880
[Guest]: where you're just helping households be protected against unfair trade practices.

00:33:00.880 --> 00:33:03.760
[Guest]: Case two is called microprudential regulation,

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:08.880
[Guest]: where we don't allow the financial firms to collapse too often.

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:11.600
[Guest]: Element three is called resolution,

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:15.120
[Guest]: which is a specialized bankruptcy code for financial firms.

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:18.240
[Guest]: And case four is called systemic risk regulation,

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:23.200
[Guest]: where you deal with the possibility of the entire financial system collapsing in a crisis.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:27.440
[Guest]: These four functions are required to be performed by a government apparatus.

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:32.160
[Guest]: OK, now what goes wrong is all too often such government apparatus

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:33.440
[Guest]: turns into central planning.

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:35.040
[Guest]: OK, and that is indeed where we came from.

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:41.920
[Guest]: Not so long ago, there was not a whiff of a normal financial market system in India,

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:43.600
[Guest]: and all we had was central planning.

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:46.560
[Guest]: And we are constantly torn between these impulses.

00:33:46.560 --> 00:33:50.720
[Guest]: So what we in India are at is the early stages of understanding

00:33:51.360 --> 00:33:53.920
[Guest]: what is the role of finance in society,

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:59.200
[Guest]: and of reorienting the government machinery away from central planning,

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:03.920
[Guest]: from controlling all the prices of time rather than only being in the short end,

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:10.000
[Guest]: and actually producing these four kinds of responses correctly and efficiently.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:10.960
[Guest]: And many things go wrong.

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:12.880
[Guest]: So I'm not here to say we are sorted.

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:17.200
[Guest]: I'm not here to say we have a well-functioning financial system in India.

00:34:17.200 --> 00:34:21.040
[Guest]: I'm not here to say that our government machinery

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:23.200
[Guest]: for doing these four kinds of things is in place.

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:28.080
[Guest]: But I am here to say that this is the kind of role

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:33.440
[Guest]: that the financial system should be playing in a market economy.

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:36.960
[Guest]: And this is the kind of world that we have to build around us in India.

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:41.040
[Amit Varma]: So one of the dangers you pointed out of an unregulated financial system

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:44.000
[Amit Varma]: and where the government needs to step in is externalities.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, you know, this brings me to the example of the 2008 crisis.

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:52.800
[Amit Varma]: And again, your points two and four microprudential and then systemic risk.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the US government, of course,

00:34:54.640 --> 00:34:58.400
[Amit Varma]: bailed out AIG and Fannie and Freddie and so on in 2008,

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:02.080
[Amit Varma]: allowed Lehman to collapse because there was what they called a systemic risk.

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:06.560
[Amit Varma]: And then pumped in a lot of money and basically bailed a whole lot of them out.

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Instead of letting them collapse, as you would expect,

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:12.400
[Amit Varma]: if you, you know, just followed the path of creative destruction,

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:13.920
[Amit Varma]: as you described in a previous episode.

00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:17.520
[Amit Varma]: So my question is that, doesn't this lead to moral hazard,

00:35:17.520 --> 00:35:21.200
[Amit Varma]: where you're basically privatizing profits, socializing losses,

00:35:21.200 --> 00:35:24.720
[Amit Varma]: and therefore any big financial firm or bank can just say that,

00:35:24.720 --> 00:35:27.920
[Amit Varma]: hey, I'll do whatever, I'll gamble with my money.

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:31.040
[Amit Varma]: If I win, I keep it. If I lose, the government's bailed me out.

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:35.680
[Guest]: There's no question that there is a threat of moral hazard.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:40.720
[Guest]: But let me first show the problem in its most extreme form.

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:42.960
[Guest]: And then let's think about what governments have done

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:44.640
[Guest]: and how you would do things differently.

00:35:44.640 --> 00:35:46.160
[Guest]: Here's the most extreme form.

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:48.160
[Guest]: I'm a trader working in a bank.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:54.880
[Guest]: I am given a million dollar bonus if I make a lot of money.

00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:58.080
[Guest]: Okay, so the game is well understood to me

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:01.600
[Guest]: that if I make $5 million in profit this year,

00:36:01.600 --> 00:36:03.360
[Guest]: I will be given a bonus of $1 million.

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:06.160
[Guest]: What is the incentive of the trader?

00:36:06.160 --> 00:36:09.520
[Guest]: The incentive of the trader is to make a Hail Mary pass,

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:11.120
[Guest]: to take very, very, very high risk.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.920
[Guest]: If it works great, I make my organization a lot of money

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:18.880
[Guest]: and I make a million dollar bonus.

00:36:18.880 --> 00:36:20.800
[Guest]: If the trade doesn't work out, how bad does it get?

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:22.880
[Guest]: I lose my job. That's not so bad.

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:25.440
[Guest]: Okay, so there's a fundamental incentive

00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:28.320
[Guest]: of employees of financial firms to roll the dice.

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:32.160
[Guest]: And that's what microprudential regulation is all about,

00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:35.520
[Guest]: to limit the risks taken by the financial firms.

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:36.960
[Guest]: And the moment I have said this,

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:39.520
[Guest]: you will shake your head in unhappiness

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:43.200
[Guest]: that do you really expect officials of some government agency

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:47.360
[Guest]: to understand the richness and complexity of the risks

00:36:47.360 --> 00:36:51.280
[Guest]: that are taken by the employees of some private financial firm

00:36:51.280 --> 00:36:53.360
[Guest]: and really be able to limit that risk?

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:55.360
[Guest]: So microprudential regulation is hard.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:57.840
[Guest]: Okay, and this is the battle that we are placed in,

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:01.120
[Guest]: that the basic incentive of private financial firms

00:37:01.120 --> 00:37:02.480
[Guest]: is to take a large risk.

00:37:02.480 --> 00:37:05.680
[Guest]: Now, there are structures that will do it better than others.

00:37:05.680 --> 00:37:07.360
[Guest]: For example, I think it's always better

00:37:07.360 --> 00:37:09.600
[Guest]: if you and I as individuals are traders,

00:37:09.600 --> 00:37:10.480
[Guest]: because it's my risk.

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:11.760
[Guest]: I've internalized that risk.

00:37:11.760 --> 00:37:13.360
[Guest]: I'm not part of a corporation.

00:37:13.360 --> 00:37:14.800
[Guest]: This is why I always favor

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:18.000
[Guest]: more direct individual participation in markets.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:19.760
[Guest]: Because once you get into institutions,

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:21.360
[Guest]: it becomes more complicated.

00:37:21.360 --> 00:37:24.320
[Guest]: Then structures like hedge funds are fundamentally better

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:27.120
[Guest]: because the returns are aligned

00:37:27.120 --> 00:37:29.360
[Guest]: with the performance that investors get.

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:31.920
[Guest]: And structures like banks are the most dangerous

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:33.840
[Guest]: because there is a balance sheet

00:37:33.840 --> 00:37:35.200
[Guest]: and there's a lot of leverage.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:36.880
[Guest]: And this is where you get the most trouble.

00:37:38.480 --> 00:37:41.600
[Guest]: Now, when the government fails

00:37:41.600 --> 00:37:43.600
[Guest]: on its microprudential regulation

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:47.840
[Guest]: or when the government fails on its systemic risk reduction,

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: you can get some big messes.

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:54.400
[Guest]: Exposed, many of us feel very uncomfortable

00:37:54.400 --> 00:37:56.160
[Guest]: about bailouts by the government.

00:37:56.160 --> 00:37:59.760
[Guest]: Okay, it is the clear use of taxpayer money

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:04.400
[Guest]: to clean up for the bad things done by fat cats

00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:06.640
[Guest]: who have been buying yachts and private planes.

00:38:06.640 --> 00:38:10.080
[Guest]: Okay, the injustice of this is palpable

00:38:10.080 --> 00:38:12.240
[Guest]: and there is no way to gloss over it.

00:38:13.120 --> 00:38:15.840
[Guest]: I just want to say to you that from the other side,

00:38:17.120 --> 00:38:18.960
[Guest]: nobody feels differently.

00:38:18.960 --> 00:38:24.000
[Guest]: So I worked on the cleanup after the UTI crisis in India.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:25.520
[Guest]: And I've had extensive conversations

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:28.320
[Guest]: with some of the people who worked in the United States

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:32.400
[Guest]: in fixing things after the global crisis.

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:33.920
[Guest]: There's not a single person there

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:36.800
[Guest]: who has the slightest attraction

00:38:36.800 --> 00:38:38.240
[Guest]: with bailing out the fat cats.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:43.200
[Guest]: The point is that the alternative was worse.

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:47.040
[Guest]: So I am persuaded that if the AIG

00:38:47.680 --> 00:38:50.320
[Guest]: and other bailouts had not happened in the United States,

00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:54.320
[Guest]: at the cost of a lot of money to the taxpayer in the short run,

00:38:54.320 --> 00:38:56.160
[Guest]: the alternative would have been worse.

00:38:56.160 --> 00:38:57.200
[Guest]: And in the United States,

00:38:57.840 --> 00:38:59.680
[Guest]: a lot of that money eventually came back.

00:38:59.680 --> 00:39:01.280
[Guest]: So in India's case also,

00:39:01.280 --> 00:39:04.800
[Guest]: the public money that went into solving the UTI problem,

00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:06.400
[Guest]: it eventually came back with interest.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:08.320
[Guest]: So the government made good

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:10.960
[Guest]: and in fact made a profit on the UTI rescue.

00:39:10.960 --> 00:39:13.360
[Guest]: So it's not that obvious exposed

00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:14.880
[Guest]: that a lot of money was put in.

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:16.880
[Guest]: But the point is clear in my mind,

00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:19.680
[Guest]: on the date when these decisions were taken,

00:39:19.680 --> 00:39:21.280
[Guest]: that the alternative was worse.

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:23.680
[Guest]: That if you just let UTI flame out

00:39:23.680 --> 00:39:25.360
[Guest]: without any public intervention,

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:28.560
[Guest]: which is closer to the sorts of things

00:39:28.560 --> 00:39:30.960
[Guest]: that a more hot-headed person,

00:39:31.680 --> 00:39:32.880
[Guest]: namely yours truly,

00:39:32.880 --> 00:39:34.560
[Guest]: used to think in those days.

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:36.000
[Guest]: Not doing anything was worse

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:37.840
[Guest]: than doing something using public money.

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:41.520
[Guest]: So I'm less religious about these matters today.

00:39:41.520 --> 00:39:43.520
[Guest]: I think we should corely look at the situation

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:46.240
[Guest]: and we should do things that are wise and sensible,

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:48.720
[Guest]: even when it appears horrible.

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:51.280
[Guest]: And there will always be the rhetoric

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:53.840
[Guest]: that the fat cats have their yachts

00:39:53.840 --> 00:39:56.160
[Guest]: and you're using precious taxpayer money

00:39:56.160 --> 00:39:57.520
[Guest]: to cover up for their mistakes.

00:39:57.520 --> 00:39:59.200
[Guest]: There is no running away from that rhetoric

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:02.480
[Guest]: and we have to think sensibly despite that.

00:40:02.480 --> 00:40:04.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I look at the sort of the marketplace of things

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:05.760
[Amit Varma]: as it were.

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:07.360
[Amit Varma]: And the whole idea is that companies

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:08.160
[Amit Varma]: which make mistakes,

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:10.640
[Amit Varma]: for example, companies which set bad incentives

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:12.160
[Amit Varma]: for their employees,

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:14.240
[Amit Varma]: like the financial firm as an analogy,

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:15.680
[Amit Varma]: which might set a bad incentive

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:17.520
[Amit Varma]: for the trader to get his million dollar bonus.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:19.840
[Amit Varma]: When companies in the marketplace of things

00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:20.800
[Amit Varma]: make mistakes like that,

00:40:20.800 --> 00:40:22.240
[Amit Varma]: they suffer for it in the balance sheet.

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:24.160
[Amit Varma]: They shut down, they're allowed to shut down.

00:40:24.160 --> 00:40:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's a lesson for everybody.

00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's how good practices creep into the thing.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.720
[Amit Varma]: But your point is that there is so much at stake

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:32.640
[Amit Varma]: in this bigger world of finance

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:35.120
[Amit Varma]: that sometimes you have to bail these guys out.

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:36.720
[Amit Varma]: And the problem of moral hazard,

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:38.960
[Amit Varma]: therefore, is ever present.

00:40:38.960 --> 00:40:40.800
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, this could just be a cycle.

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:41.680
[Guest]: It could happen again.

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:42.880
[Guest]: Yes, it will happen again.

00:40:42.880 --> 00:40:44.400
[Guest]: It will assuredly happen again.

00:40:44.400 --> 00:40:45.840
[Guest]: First, I want to say that,

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:47.760
[Guest]: please do not underestimate the damage

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:50.400
[Guest]: that was caused to the shareholders of AIG,

00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:51.920
[Guest]: to the top managers of AIG,

00:40:51.920 --> 00:40:52.960
[Guest]: they were wiped out.

00:40:52.960 --> 00:40:55.200
[Guest]: Okay, so it's not as if

00:40:55.760 --> 00:40:57.200
[Guest]: they are directly getting money.

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:58.480
[Guest]: The more complex thing is

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:00.080
[Guest]: they made a bonus the previous year.

00:41:00.080 --> 00:41:02.000
[Guest]: Okay, so for the previous 10 years,

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.160
[Guest]: they had taken home fabulous bonuses.

00:41:04.160 --> 00:41:07.440
[Guest]: They were buying islands in the Bahamas.

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:09.040
[Amit Varma]: And nobody can change that.

00:41:09.040 --> 00:41:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Privatized profits,

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and they knew the losses would be socialized.

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:16.000
[Guest]: So when AIG got public money,

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:17.840
[Guest]: the existing shareholders were wiped out,

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:19.200
[Guest]: much like a bankruptcy process.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:19.680
[Guest]: Sure.

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:23.600
[Guest]: Now, the reason why the world of things

00:41:23.600 --> 00:41:25.040
[Guest]: is different from the world of finance

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:26.400
[Guest]: is exactly where we started.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:29.840
[Guest]: That finance is the brain of the economy.

00:41:29.840 --> 00:41:32.240
[Guest]: So the amount of damage that you can do

00:41:32.240 --> 00:41:34.480
[Guest]: by destroying the financial firms is extreme.

00:41:34.480 --> 00:41:36.240
[Guest]: So I said that

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:37.840
[Guest]: if there was a giant earthquake in Bombay

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:39.280
[Guest]: and everything was destroyed,

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:40.320
[Guest]: where would you start?

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:42.080
[Guest]: You would start by rebuilding the financial sector.

00:41:42.080 --> 00:41:43.360
[Guest]: Now, let me flip this around.

00:41:43.360 --> 00:41:45.120
[Guest]: Let me leave the rest of Bombay intact.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:47.040
[Guest]: And let me destroy all the financial firms.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:48.960
[Guest]: Let me destroy the financial markets.

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:50.160
[Guest]: That would be a catastrophe.

00:41:50.160 --> 00:41:51.840
[Guest]: The world of things would not work

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:53.440
[Guest]: if the world of finance was not there.

00:41:53.440 --> 00:41:55.680
[Guest]: So because finance is so important,

00:41:55.680 --> 00:41:57.600
[Guest]: a disruption of the financial system

00:41:57.600 --> 00:41:59.520
[Guest]: is disproportionately important,

00:41:59.520 --> 00:42:00.640
[Guest]: and it does damage.

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:04.640
[Guest]: So there is a really bad problem

00:42:04.640 --> 00:42:05.680
[Guest]: in what you're describing,

00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:08.720
[Guest]: and you are absolutely correct to highlight it.

00:42:08.720 --> 00:42:11.200
[Guest]: It's a tough thing that we will need to confront.

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:13.600
[Guest]: So my good word will be,

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:16.160
[Guest]: can we do better on microprudential regulation?

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:18.880
[Guest]: Can we do better on systemic risk management?

00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:21.200
[Guest]: So that these things don't happen to us.

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:23.280
[Guest]: And I think there's a lot of headroom

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:25.040
[Guest]: for us in India to do these things.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:27.920
[Guest]: That said, yes, I feel pretty certain

00:42:27.920 --> 00:42:28.960
[Guest]: that in the next 20 years,

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:29.920
[Guest]: we will have one more mess.

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:31.440
[Amit Varma]: Why do you say that?

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:33.520
[Guest]: Because it is in the nature of finance

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:34.720
[Guest]: for these things to happen.

00:42:34.720 --> 00:42:38.080
[Guest]: Let me say this in a somewhat more sophisticated way.

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:42.800
[Guest]: I said that there is a trader in a financial firm

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:44.640
[Guest]: and the boss of the trader

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:46.480
[Guest]: or the regulator of the bank

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:47.920
[Guest]: is trying to control the risk

00:42:47.920 --> 00:42:48.880
[Guest]: that this guy is taking.

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:51.440
[Guest]: But that trader is sitting at the desk

00:42:51.440 --> 00:42:52.880
[Guest]: and thinking day and night.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:54.480
[Guest]: The trader will always find

00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:56.960
[Guest]: that complicated oddball position

00:42:56.960 --> 00:42:58.240
[Guest]: that can be taken,

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:00.480
[Guest]: where the risk as calculated

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:03.440
[Guest]: by his boss or his regulator will be wrong.

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:06.720
[Guest]: So the world is a complicated place.

00:43:06.720 --> 00:43:08.160
[Guest]: No models are perfect.

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:11.280
[Guest]: Every attempt by a regulator or by a management

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:12.720
[Guest]: to measure and control the risk

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:15.280
[Guest]: that is being taken by the decision makers.

00:43:16.240 --> 00:43:17.920
[Guest]: These attempts will always be crude.

00:43:17.920 --> 00:43:20.000
[Guest]: And the moment you put in a system,

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:21.920
[Guest]: the moment you put in a risk system,

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:23.440
[Guest]: there are very, very smart people

00:43:23.440 --> 00:43:25.360
[Guest]: who are trying to find the chinks

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:26.800
[Guest]: of that risk system.

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:27.920
[Guest]: And the world will change

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:29.600
[Guest]: and there will be opportunities

00:43:29.600 --> 00:43:31.280
[Guest]: to load up on risk in ways

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:33.440
[Guest]: that your risk model does not quite see.

00:43:33.440 --> 00:43:35.200
[Guest]: And then the cycle will start all over again.

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:36.880
[Guest]: So it's just in the nature of the world

00:43:36.880 --> 00:43:38.160
[Guest]: that the world will change.

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:39.920
[Guest]: The class of instruments will change.

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:41.360
[Guest]: Every risk system is limited.

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:42.480
[Guest]: We will have a mess

00:43:42.480 --> 00:43:43.280
[Guest]: and then we'll clean up

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:44.320
[Guest]: and we'll start over.

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:46.640
[Amit Varma]: So now you're someone who's known

00:43:46.640 --> 00:43:48.720
[Amit Varma]: the Indian financial system intimately,

00:43:48.720 --> 00:43:50.480
[Amit Varma]: both as part of the establishment

00:43:50.480 --> 00:43:51.760
[Amit Varma]: and as a reformer

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:53.120
[Amit Varma]: and perhaps as a player.

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:54.800
[Amit Varma]: So in your view, very broadly,

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:57.120
[Amit Varma]: what is wrong with the Indian financial system today?

00:43:57.840 --> 00:43:59.440
[Guest]: In India, we started at a legacy

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:01.920
[Guest]: of a 1934 RBI Act.

00:44:02.720 --> 00:44:04.720
[Guest]: When the British created that act

00:44:04.720 --> 00:44:06.320
[Guest]: in a remarkable act of honesty,

00:44:06.880 --> 00:44:10.000
[Guest]: in the first two sentences of the law,

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.640
[Guest]: they said that as a temporary measure,

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:14.160
[Guest]: we create the Reserve Bank of India.

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:15.920
[Guest]: Okay, so this is not a structure

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:17.920
[Guest]: that was intended to be a thorough,

00:44:17.920 --> 00:44:18.960
[Guest]: well thought out thing.

00:44:19.520 --> 00:44:22.160
[Guest]: And it has taken many, many years.

00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:24.640
[Guest]: So we started with that temporary structure

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:26.480
[Guest]: in the years of Indian socialism.

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:28.320
[Guest]: We built an entire financial system

00:44:28.320 --> 00:44:29.840
[Guest]: around central planning.

00:44:29.840 --> 00:44:31.680
[Guest]: So the idea was that the planning commission

00:44:31.680 --> 00:44:33.600
[Guest]: would decide there needs to be a steel mill

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:36.240
[Guest]: and the financial system will serve up

00:44:36.240 --> 00:44:38.320
[Guest]: the money required to build that steel mill.

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:39.280
[Guest]: That's our legacy.

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:40.640
[Guest]: That's where we started.

00:44:40.640 --> 00:44:42.800
[Guest]: We started getting some new organizations

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:43.440
[Guest]: like SEBI,

00:44:44.240 --> 00:44:45.520
[Guest]: but in the 90s,

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:48.400
[Guest]: when the DNA of the organization was laid,

00:44:48.400 --> 00:44:49.680
[Guest]: we did not know a whole lot

00:44:49.680 --> 00:44:52.800
[Guest]: about how to create the processes

00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:55.040
[Guest]: and the checks and balances

00:44:55.600 --> 00:44:56.880
[Guest]: of these organizations.

00:44:56.880 --> 00:44:59.840
[Guest]: I think only in the last five, 10 years,

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:01.280
[Guest]: we've developed a good understanding

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:03.280
[Guest]: about what is to be done.

00:45:03.280 --> 00:45:06.000
[Guest]: I check pointed the four things to you.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:07.360
[Guest]: We need to do consumer protection,

00:45:07.360 --> 00:45:08.880
[Guest]: microprudential regulation,

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.360
[Guest]: resolution and systemic risk.

00:45:11.360 --> 00:45:14.480
[Guest]: This clarity is only last five, 10 years.

00:45:15.040 --> 00:45:17.200
[Guest]: And we also have a lot of clarity

00:45:17.200 --> 00:45:20.400
[Guest]: on how a regulator should work,

00:45:20.400 --> 00:45:22.240
[Guest]: how to create checks and balances,

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:24.160
[Guest]: how to prevent arbitrary power,

00:45:24.160 --> 00:45:26.240
[Guest]: how to prevent arbitrary persecution

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:27.840
[Guest]: by a regulator.

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:30.240
[Guest]: These are things that we've only started understanding

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:31.680
[Guest]: in the last five, 10 years.

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:33.680
[Guest]: So I think only now we're coming to the point

00:45:33.680 --> 00:45:35.840
[Guest]: where we have a reasonable understanding

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:38.720
[Guest]: of what is the task of financial regulation

00:45:38.720 --> 00:45:41.360
[Guest]: and what is the kind of organizational design

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.320
[Guest]: and law and public administration

00:45:44.320 --> 00:45:47.600
[Guest]: that will take us towards state capability,

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:50.160
[Guest]: state capacity in doing this kind of work.

00:45:50.160 --> 00:45:51.440
[Guest]: And in the meantime,

00:45:51.440 --> 00:45:53.520
[Guest]: there are these incumbents in the landscape.

00:45:53.520 --> 00:45:55.760
[Guest]: There are public sector firms in the landscape.

00:45:55.760 --> 00:45:57.520
[Guest]: So there will be resistance.

00:45:57.520 --> 00:45:59.440
[Guest]: So I see a long, slow journey

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:03.680
[Guest]: of building the state capability

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:06.480
[Guest]: to do the right things

00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:08.080
[Guest]: and not do the central planning.

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:10.000
[Amit Varma]: What are the big specific reforms

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:10.800
[Amit Varma]: you'd carry out

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:13.280
[Amit Varma]: if you were in charge of the finance ministry tomorrow?

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:17.200
[Guest]: I was a bit player in a very important project

00:46:17.840 --> 00:46:19.760
[Guest]: that was begun in 2011.

00:46:19.760 --> 00:46:21.760
[Guest]: It is called the Financial Sector

00:46:21.760 --> 00:46:23.760
[Guest]: Legislative Reforms Commission.

00:46:23.760 --> 00:46:26.000
[Guest]: And this blueprint was set up there.

00:46:26.560 --> 00:46:30.160
[Guest]: This commission was led by Justice Shri Krishna.

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:32.800
[Guest]: And the report was submitted in 2013

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:35.360
[Guest]: and the work was completed in 2015.

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:36.800
[Guest]: It's a single clean law.

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:38.400
[Guest]: It's called the Indian Financial Code.

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:40.480
[Guest]: And in my mind,

00:46:40.480 --> 00:46:43.120
[Guest]: that's a very important reform to enact this law.

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:46.240
[Guest]: It replaces 61 existing laws.

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:48.320
[Guest]: And then there would be several years of work

00:46:48.320 --> 00:46:50.880
[Guest]: on building the agency architecture

00:46:50.880 --> 00:46:53.200
[Guest]: that would be able to enforce this law.

